We got a set of new batteries (black) from Andymark this season, and I was going through our bot and ended up weighing them, and was surprised they were 11lbs. The grey ones we got in our KOP were all 13.4lbs give or take. That is a huge difference, should we be concerned? AndyMark lists them as being 12.5lbs with the grey being 12.89lbs so there is a difference, but not as much as what we got.

We ordered several of the black (Interstate) in our case batteries from Andymark and tested them on the CBA analyzer and only 2 of the 6 were good per Andymark’s instructions with the analyzer.

They should be above 12Ah and we had them ranging from 4 to 10 Ah.

We reached out to Andymark and they took care of us, but I would make sure you test the batteries before you trust them in a competition.

I did not weigh them, so I don’t know if that has any factor. I may try that when I have a chance.

Computerized Battery Analyzer - AndyMark, Inc

Yes be aware we ordered the Interstate (black) batteries last year and they all turned out to be complete garbage. We reverted back to the gray MK batteries. The black Interstate batteries did not hold a charge at all during peak competition matches and hindered us. Be sure to check them and return if needed.

I would suggest you use those batteries for practice only or other uses and save the good ones for competition use. I am not an RI this year so things might have changed, though I doubt that for battery construction.

Yep. Our team was in the same boat and at the end of the last years season, myself and some of the mentors did extensive testing via the competition robot and also letting the batteries sit. Both tests showed that the batteries we received were defective and couldn’t hold a charge even for a 2:30 match time of drive train practice. We were not happy with our purchase and will never purchase them again.

Don’t just accept you’ve received a defective product, and loose out on the money tied up in said product.

We were in the market for light batteries last year and weighed all of ours, and discovered that the (black) Interstate ones were around 11 lb, where the (gray) MK ones were around 13 lb, so we went out of our way to buy more Interstate ones.

None of the Interstate batteries we bought in early 2023 survived to our off-season event in the fall.

The MK Battery that we got in the 2021(?) kit of parts is still doing well.

We wouldn’t buy Interstate again.

Edit: I should mention that the Interstate batteries we bought were not from an FRC vendor.

Battery Warning FIRST
Gonna chime in here. Our kop battery (SPS brand) performed the worst on our battery tests out of 14 batteries from 2016, 2017, 2018, and 2019. An interesting side note: The mean weight of 12 of the 13 batteries that aren’t from the 2019 kop (the 13th battery was not available for weighing) is 13 lbs with a standard deviation of 0.37 lbs. Our kop battery weighs 11.4 lbs. Not sure if this is significant, but I found it interesting.

Hi chadr03. That’s interesting. Did you cycle (discharge/recharge) the battery several times before taking measurements with the CBA?

A factory activated VRLA AGM (or SLA) battery sitting for some time on the shelf will not perform well and reach its rated capacity until you complete enough of these cycles. How many cycles depends on the current state of charge (SoC), storage temperature, and time not connected to a charger that provides a continuous maintenance voltage to your battery, keeping chemistry and sulfation from working against you. The moment the factory chemically activates a battery, provides an initial charge, and removes the battery from the charger, ready to be boxed and shipped, the battery chemistry goes to work creating crystals of lead sulfate that continue to grow and reduce battery capacity. Left unchecked, ALL lead-acid batteries will naturally sulfate themselves to death, or what is usually called an expired battery. I have found that the number of cycles needed for a MK or Interstate battery to be about 3-4 discharge/charge cycles before they behave and start to produce a family of Discharge Time vs. Current curves similar to that published by the manufacturer.

On another post, you mentioned you were getting good performance results from Interstate batteries, and except for the cases of several early failures, which speaks more to the batteries’ RELIABILITY rather than performance, the Interstate battery performance exceeded that of the MK batteries. I can validate your claim, after taking carefully controlled measurements, with batteries from similar date lots, under the same charging conditions, times, and temperatures. I think this has much more to do with specsmanship on the part of the battery manufacturer which I won’t go into detail here until I study this further.

As for battery state of health (SoH) we are monitoring them, our MK and Interstate alike to determine the reliability and SoH for both.

I do not have much information on the number of charge/discharge cycles prior to testing of the new batteries. I know most if not all had a few. We typically order about 6 new batteries every year. Give them names and then we will practice and tune our robot with them to get a few charge cycles. Then about a week before competition we will start doing CBA testing on all of our batteries to see what will go with us to comp. We have not historically tracked which batteries we practice with to make sure they all get even usage and similar charge cycles, but we might need to start that.

So, it is possible that we did not have enough charge cycles prior to testing, but on the new batteries that failed have done at least two full CBA tests some of them three and had similar results on all.

We also had similar issues with a pair of new Interstate batteries from AndyMark – had some brownouts in week 1 during a practice match, pulled the first one from rotation, then had problems with the second one near the end of a qual match and pulled it too. There was no attempt to cycle these before competition – ran out of time. All we did was charge them up until the charger said they were ready, then Beaked them.

Afterwards, I took them home and put together a test rig: 0-600A electronic load, two DMMs with GPIB. One of the batteries tested marginally okay (comparable to our most worn batteries); the other died partway through testing.

As I was still messing around with this crude thing, I didn’t do much in the way of scientific testing – some of the runs shows where I dropped the load current to zero a few times to get an idea of the open-circuit voltage, and when the actually-dead battery (2023batt5…) died, I dropped the current to zero for a while, attempted to resume a few times, then tried various lower load currents to see how bad the battery actually was.

I ran these pretty hard – 50A, until they hit 10.5V loaded and (ideally) recovered to 12.0V OC. Not sure if that’s sufficiently representative, but it’s what I did.
